haefeleuser wrote:

&gt; Someone in our team writes his tests like this:
&gt;
&gt; try
&gt; {
&gt;   articleProvider.findArticleById(&quot;foobar&quot;);
&gt; }
&gt; catch(NoObjectFoundException e)
&gt; {
&gt;   assertTrue(true);
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; He says the does it because otherwise Checkstyle would complain about
&gt; the empty catch block.
&gt;
&gt; I do it in this manner:
&gt;
&gt; try
&gt; {
&gt;   articleProvider.findArticleById(&quot;foobar&quot;);
&gt; }
&gt; catch(NoObjectFoundException e)
&gt; {
&gt;   // Its okay since we expect it.
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; What do you prefer in the case above: assertTrue(true) or inline
&gt; comment in the catch block?


I prefer:

try {
    articleProvider.findArticleById(&quot;foobar&quot;);
    fail(&quot;Expected NoObjectFoundException);
} catch (Exception e) {
    assertSame(e.getClass(), NoObjectFoundException.class);
    // or whatever else seems appropriate (eg. testing getMessage() or 
other attribute)
}

-- 
